article.description: The Flames extended their dominance of the Big South Conference and claimed their 12th NCAA tournament appearance by beating Gardner-Webb 51-50 in the title game Sunday, a victory sealed by a defensive stop in the final seconds.
article.headline: Liberty survives Gardner-Webb to win 12th Big South title in 13 years
article.linkText: Liberty extends dominance in Big South with win
article.story:
HIGH POINT, N.C. -- Rachel Hammond and Megan Frazee took a few steps away from the podium when they turned around, realizing they left something behind: Their slivers of net from the championship game.

It's pretty easy to lose track of all the nets they've cut down lately at Liberty.

The Flames extended their dominance of the Big South Conference and claimed their 12th NCAA tournament appearance by beating Gardner-Webb 51-50 in the title game Sunday, a victory sealed by a defensive stop in the final seconds.

Hammond scored 13 points while Frazee, the league's player of the year and tournament MVP, added 12 and sister Moriah Frazee finished with 10 for top-seeded Liberty (24-8). The Flames held a 51-25 rebounding advantage and overcame 17 turnovers to win their 23rd in 25 games while capturing the league for the 12th time in 13 years.

"I knew that I didn't want it to be my last game," said Hammond, one of five seniors on the Liberty roster. "That's all I was thinking about."

Courtney Epps scored 21 points for the Runnin' Bulldogs (17-15), and her contested layup with 53 seconds remaining made it a one-point game. Liberty turned it over with 24 seconds left when Hammond tossed up an airball as the shot clock expired, and Gardner-Webb brought the ball upcourt and called timeout with 12 seconds remaining.

Dominique Hudson dribbled out much of the clock before making her move, taking Hammond down the right side of the lane with about 5 seconds left. But Hammond never allowed her a clean look, and Hudson's drive with three Liberty defenders in her face rolled around the rim before bouncing out at the horn.

"I knew that, obviously, Hudson was going to take it, and she waited for such a long time that it was really going to be [only] one shot up," Hammond said. "I was laying on the ground and it was rolling around, and it really was going to go in. ... I was just thinking, 'Don't go in,' and it didn't go in."

Added Hudson in a hushed tone: "I just missed it."

Hudson -- whose late free throws one day earlier keyed her team's semifinal win over second-seeded High Point -- finished with 10 points for the senior-free Runnin' Bulldogs. They went 7-9 during their first season since leaving the Atlantic Sun for the Big South, but were denied both their third upset in three days and their first automatic bid to the NCAA tournament since joining Division I in 2000.

"We're growing as a team and the maturity factor is still been so positive for us," Gardner-Webb coach Rick Reeves said. "But we're still young. We make some young mistakes."

Liberty coach Carey Green improved to 27-1 in the Big South tournament and claimed his ninth conference title by beating the coach who started the Flames' current run of dominance. Reeves won the league three times from 1997-99 and recommended Green for the job when he left for Southern Mississippi. He arrived at Gardner-Webb in 2004.

"I'm grateful for him for encouraging me to pursue the job at Liberty," Green said. "I can understand why it would be difficult for him -- he loves Liberty, and he invested a lot of his time ... and he experienced championships here."

Now comes the next challenge for Liberty: Carrying that success over into the NCAAs. The Flames are 2-11 in the big tournament, with both victories coming during their run to the round of 16 in 2005.

"We're not finished yet," Green said. "I know the seniors, they want more, and they're capable of doing more."

Liberty seemed to have taken control by outscoring the Runnin' Bulldogs 24-9 to start the second half while holding Gardner-Webb without a field goal for more than 7 minutes. Amber Mays' steal and layup with 7 1/2 minutes put the Flames up 47-37 -- the only double-figure lead for either team.

"We said, 'Just lay your heart out on the floor,'" Reeves said, urging his Runnin' Bulldogs "to give me total effort for a lifetime memory. I've been to the NCAA tournament -- it's quite an experience for kids, something they'll remember all their life. And they did."

The Flames claimed their latest league title despite an off game from their best player. Megan Frazee, who entered averaging a Big South-best 27 points, matched her least-productive game of the season -- she also was held to 12 two months ago against Coastal Carolina -- and was just 4-of-12 shooting with the smaller Runnin' Bulldogs constantly pestering her. For just the third time in 22 games, she wasn't the Flames' leading scorer. Foul trouble limited her to only 23 minutes -- 12 fewer than her average.

"As a player, you like to be on the court if at all possible," she said. "I was a little frustrated sitting on the bench, but that happens sometimes ... but you've just got to play through it and keep going."

She was part of Liberty's imposing front line that started three 6-foot-3 players. Gardner-Webb doesn't have anybody that tall on the roster, one reason the Flames allowed the Runnin' Bulldogs only six offensive rebounds -- none in the first 14 minutes. Avery Warley finished with 17 rebounds, 14 on the defensive end, to lead Liberty's dominance on the glass.
